Change the merge operation from sum to min:
Pseudocode


```
def build(arr,node,start,end):
    if start==end:
        tree[node]=arr[start]
    else:
        mid=(start+end)// 2
        build(arr,2*node,start,mid)build(arr,2*node+1,mid+1,end)tree[node]=min(tree[2*node],tree[2*node+1])def query(node,start,end,l,r):
    if r < start or end < l:
        return float('inf')# identity for min
    if l <=start and end <=r:
        return tree[node]
    mid=(start+end)// 2
    return min(query(2*node,start,mid,l,r),query(2*node+1,mid+1,end,l,r))
```

The identity element changes: 0 for sum,∞ for min,−∞ for max,1 for product.
Same O(logn)complexity for all operations.

Iterative segment trees are faster in practice(no recursion overhead)and use exactly 2n space:
Pseudocode


```
class IterativeSegTree:
    function init(arr):
        this.n=arr.length
        this.tree=array of 2*this.n zeros
        // Build: leaves at positions n to 2n-1
        for i from 0 to this.n - 1:
            this.tree[this.n+i]=arr[i]
        for i from this.n - 1 down to 1:
            this.tree[i]=this.tree[2*i]+this.tree[2*i+1]

```

Leaves are stored in positions n to 2n−1. Internal nodes in positions 1 to n−1. Position 0 is unused.
This layout is more cache-friendly and avoids the 4n space overhead.

Pseudocode


```
class NumArray:
    function init(nums):
        this.n=nums.length
        this.nums=copy(nums)this.tree=array of size(this.n+1),filled with 0
        for i=0 to nums.length - 1:
            this._add(i+1,nums[i])function _add(i,delta):
        while i <=this.n:
            this.tree[i]+=delta
            i+=i &(-i)function _prefix(i):
        result=0
        while i > 0:
            result+=this.tree[i]
            i -=i &(-i)return result

    function update(index,val):
        delta=val - this.nums[index]
        this.nums[index]=val
        this._add(index+1,delta)function sumRange(left,right):
        return this._prefix(right+1)- this._prefix(left)
```

